Hi Tim,

Thanks - that's really helpful and has reduced the complexity somewhat.

I had another (hopefully) quick question about the order in which some variables are updated. Specifically, AOS_Solution() runs AOS_CapillaryRise(), then crop development modules, then soil evaporation/transpiration, then AOS_GroundwaterInflow(). Could you explain the logic of calculating capillary rise before crop development, but groundwater inflow afterwards?

Thanks a lot,
Simon

Timothy Foster writes:

> Hi Simon,
>
> Sorry for the delay replying. Been trying to stay off emails as much as possible during the strike.
>
> You shouldn’t need to change these spatially or temporally. These basically are internal model parameters that control whether crop growth occurs based on calendar days or growing degree days. My advice would probably be to specify crop growth stages (phenology) in terms of calendar days, as this build in an implicit assumption that farmers’ would adapt the variety (e.g. of wheat) that they grow to account for spatial heterogeneity in temperature conditions. The downside of this approach would be that you would have the same growing season length in a given grid cell in each individual year, which isn’t that realistic. However, might still be the easiest way to get started for now - we could revisit when we talk on Skype.
